[[Image:SihemBadi Mai2012.jpg|200px|thumb|Sihem Badi]]
'''Sihem Badi''' is a [[Tunisia]]n politician. She serves as the Minister of Women's Affairs under Prime Minister [[Hamadi Jebali]].<ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/world-leaders-1/world-leaders-t/tunisia.html CIA World Leaders]</ref><ref name="tunisialive">Wiem Melki, [http://www.tunisia-live.net/2011/12/22/sihem-badi/ Sihem Badi], ''Tunisia Live'', 22 December 2011</ref><ref name="lepoint">Sihem Sioud, [http://www.lepoint.fr/invites-du-point/sihem-souid/sihem-badi-les-craintes-sur-les-droits-des-femmes-ne-sont-pas-fondees-01-03-2012-1436748_421.php Sihem Badi : "Les craintes sur les droits des femmes ne sont pas fond<U+00E9>es"], ''[[Le Point]]'', 01/03/2012</ref>

==Biography==

===Early life===
Sihem Badi was born on June 12, 1967 in [[Tozeur]].<ref name="tunisialive"/> She received a PhD in Medical Studies from the [[University of Paris]].<ref name="tunisialive"/>

===Politics===
She is a member of the [[Congress for the Republic]] [[political party]].<ref name="tunisialive"/> In 1992, she was sentenced to two years in prison after she condemned former President [[Zine El Abidine Ben Ali]], and she went to France in exile.<ref name="lepoint"/>

On 20 December 2011, she joined the [[Jebali Cabinet]] as Minister of Women's Affairs.<ref name="tunisialive"/> She has said she would like to see more women in leadership positions.<ref>Sihem Badi : "Je veux que la femme soit pr<U+00E9>sente dans les postes de d<U+00E9>cision", ''[[Le Monde]]'', 08/03/2012</ref>

